<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Election Highlights Party Rivalries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    European Election Highlights Party Rivalries </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405140294 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1100 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405140294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Problems still remain for the new government, 
which must also deal with the rivalries impelling all the 
parties to run independently at the forthcoming European 
elections to be held on 12 June. Attilio Romita reports: 
  [Romita] All the parties have entered the fray of the 
forthcoming European elections. Following March's electoral 
earthquake, we have a new test which will weigh heavily on the 
shoulders of the new political leadership. Partial local 
elections will be held on the same day; 9 million voters 
throughout Italy will have to elect a new regional council in 
Sardinia, 11 provincial councils, and 485 town councils. The 
local elections affect 92 cities with over 15,000 [as received] 
inhabitants, and of those cities 21 are provincial capitals. 
  In the race for Strasbourg, all the parties are pitted 
against each other. Due to the system of proportional 
representation and the disappointments of March, the parties 
will run independently at the European elections -- both on the 
left and the right. The only alliance is that of the Italian 
Socialist Party and the Democratic Alliance. 
  Silvio Berlusconi will head the Forza Italia list of 
candidates. [passage omitted] 
  All the big guns will also be running in the election; 
Umberto Bossi, Gianfranco Fini, Achille Occhetto, Fausto 
Bertinotti, Mario Segni, Carlo Ripa di Meana, and Leoluca 
Orlando. Giorgio la Malfa is considering whether to participate. 
  Finally, Francesco Moser, former world cycling champion, is 
preparing to run for the Union Valdotaine. 

</TEXT>

