<H3> <TI>   Premier Welcomes Parliament Vote on EU Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Welcomes Parliament Vote on EU Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405204494 Stockholm Radio Sweden in Swedish 2000 GMT 4 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>
<F P=105>  Swedish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] After the voting at the European 
Parliament [which voted for Sweden's membership of the EU], 
Prime Minister Carl Bildt was of course pleased. 
  [Begin recording] [Bildt] This is very good news, and this 
means that the last formal obstacle to a quick signing of the 
agreements that make our membership possible from the beginning 
of next year has now been removed. 
  [Correspondent Tomas Ramberg] The biggest obstacle to your 
ambitions to enter the European Union is still there, the 
Swedish nation. Do you think this decision will have some 
influence on opinion in Sweden? 
  [Bildt] I think that possibly it will. There have been many 
who have always said that this will not succeed, it will 
collapse because of this or that, and this was maybe the last 
thing they had pinned some of their hopes on. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] The date of the national referendum where the 
Swedish nation will make a decision on EU membership will be 13 
November. 

</TEXT>

