<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Welcomes Vote </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Welcomes Vote </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0405170894 Paris AFP in English 1654 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0405170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Stockholm, May 4 (AFP) -- Swedish European Affairs 
Minister Ulf Dinkelspiel hailed the European Parliament's 
decision Wednesday [4 May] to admit Sweden, Austria, Finland and 
Norway to the European Union (EU). 
  "The Swedish Government welcomes, with great satisfaction, 
the European Parliament's decision to accept the membership 
agreement with Sweden and the three other applicant countries," 
Dinkelspiel said in a statement. 
  "Today's decision means that the decisive factor now lies in 
the hands of the Swedish people," he added. 
  Sweden is expected to hold a referendum on EU membership 
November 13. 
  "Today's decision gives a clear signal to governments and 
people -- both in member countries and applicant countries -- to 
move quickly in forming a united Europe," he said. 
  "In our opinion, Sweden has negotiated a very good agreement 
on membership in the European Union. It is very gratifying that 
the European Parliament today supports this agreement," 
Dinkelspiel concluded. 

</TEXT>

