<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agriculture Minister Announces Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agriculture Minister Announces Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405175494 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1700 GMT 
4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vicente Albero, minister of agriculture, fisheries, 
and food, has handed in his resignation to Felipe Gonzalez. The 
resignation is described as irrevocable. He is now explaining 
the reasons for this resignation at the Ministry; the reasons 
why he is voluntarily leaving his post are linked to the Ibercor 
affair. Over to our reporter Manuel de Ramon. Hello Manuel de 
Ramon, good evening. 
  [Ramon] Former Minister Vicente Albero has explained that he 
resigned because he had mortgage bonds deposited in the office 
of the former receiver of the Madrid stock market, Manuel De La 
Concha. He gave Manuel De La Concha orders saying that these 
bonds were not to be speculated with. He had obtained these 
mortgage bonds when he resigned as managing director of the 
Marie Claire hosiery company in 1982. He was managing director 
until 1982, and then he got a job as general director in the 
socialist administration. He was paid in mortgage bonds which 
he deposited in Manuel De La Concha's office. 
  Vicente Albero has repeated that he did not speculate while 
he was working as a politician and as a civil servant. He only 
worked at his job and he is not mixed up in any shady deals. 
This is all we can say just now. 

</TEXT>

