<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   BDI President Sees Opportunities in Larger EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    BDI President Sees Opportunities in Larger EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505102094 Hamburg DPA in German 0903 GMT 5 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0505102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Saarbruecken (DPA) -- German industry places great 
expectations on the enlargement of the European Union. The 
acceptance of Norway, Finland, Sweden, and Austria, which was 
approved by the European Parliament on Wednesday [4 May], 
creates additional opportunities for investments, for German 
companies also, Tyll Necker, president of the Federation of 
German Industry (BDI), said on Saarland Radio on Thursday. 
"There will be a great number of improved opportunities for 
cooperation." 
  German industry need not fear potential greater competition 
by the new members, Necker said. Rather, there is the 
opportunity for a better division of labor within Europe. Thus, 
the Nordic states are, for instance, strong regarding the 
production of cellulose. Traffic routes to Scandinavia could 
also be improved and expanded. The decisive thing is "that we 
will all become stronger in international competition through a 
larger market," Necker stressed. 

</TEXT>

