<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Increases Efforts To Close Chernobyl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Increases Efforts To Close Chernobyl </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505172094 Paris AFP in English 1704 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0505172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, May 5 (AFP) -- European Trade Commissioner 
Sir Leon Brittan will this week renew calls for the total 
closure of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant during a visit to 
Ukraine, a spokesman said Thursday [5 May]. 
  The spokesman said Brittan, due in Ukraine Thursday and 
Friday, will stress the urgent need to close the facility, the 
site of the world's worst civilian nuclear accident, in April 
1986. 
  In Paris, French Environment Minister Michel Barnier said 
Thursday his government would submit a proposal to its European 
Union [EU] allies within 10 days for a concrete timetable for 
closing the two reactors still operating at the plant. 
  Barnier said France would seek approval for the project from 
both the EU and delegates at the G7 summit of leading 
industrialised nations in Naples in July. 
  Both he and the European Commission spokesman stressed the 
need to help ensure Ukraine has stable alternative sources of 
energy. 
  Western nuclear energy experts believe Chernobyl could fall 
victim to a second disaster if the plant is not shut down. 
  Energy-starved Ukraine says Chernobyl provides seven percent 
of the former Soviet republic's electricity and that it would 
need three billion dollars in financial compensation for 
shutting it down. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

