<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis Insists Denktas Accept UN Document </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kliridhis Insists Denktas Accept UN Document </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0505115494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0505115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis has made it a 
prerequisite of his visiting New York that Turkish Cypriot 
leader Rauf Denktas accept the UN document of 21 March on the 
confidence-building measures. Government spokesman Ioannis 
Kasoulidhis today said that if Kliridhis is asked to go to New 
York, he will go with pleasure if he is told that Denktas has 
accepted the 21 March UN document. Kasoulidhis said there is no 
other reason for Kliridhis to go to New York. 
  Asked whether the government is informed about the meetings 
that Robert Lamb, the U.S. State Department special coordinator 
on the Cyprus issue, is holding in New York on the Cyprus issue, 
the government spokesman described the situation as a waiting 
period. He stressed that the government is not sitting back 
doing nothing. 
  Asked to comment on press reports today on Butrus-Ghali's 
upcoming report, Kasoulidhis said the Cypriot Government expects 
that in his report to the UN Security Council, the UN secretary 
general will attribute blame objectively for the lack of 
progress in the procedure for the confidence-building measures. 
  Kasoulidhis said that any effort not to apportion blame, 
justifying such a thing by saying that it would discourage the 
Turkish side, threatens to discourage the Greek Cypriot side 
tremendously. 
  The spokesman said that the UN secretary general's report 
will be submitted as soon as Butrus-Ghali returns to New York on 
14 May. 

</TEXT>

