<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Officials Meet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Officials Meet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0605012394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0057 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0605012394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, May 6 KYODO -- Japanese and German finance 
officials acknowledged that their economies are showing a 
similar trend with bright signs emerging in both countries, when 
they met for regular talks Thursday [5 May], a Japanese official 
said. 
  The bilateral finance meeting, designed for exchanging views 
on fiscal and economic matters, was the first in two and a half 
years and only the fifth occasion of such a meeting between the 
two countries. The Japanese and German officials agreed to hold 
the next meeting in Tokyo next year, the official said. 
  The Japanese delegation was led by Kosuke Nakahira, vice 
finance minister for international affairs. Nakahira is 
scheduled to fly to London on Friday and to Stockholm on Monday 
for bilateral financial talks. 

</TEXT>

