<H3> <TI>   Kohl Views Economic Situation at Gera Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Views Economic Situation at Gera Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0605104594 Berlin DIE WELT in German 6 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0605104594 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Kohl: Germany Is Heading Toward a </F>
Good Future"] 
  [Text] Chancellor Helmut Kohl continues to note an 
economic upturn in the new laender. "The things that have been 
already achieved here over the past three years have not even 
started in other areas," he said at an East Thuringia regional 
conference in Gera. "The GNP in eastern Germany has increased 
by over 7 percent since 1993, in Thuringia itself it has even 
increased by a double figure." 
  According to Kohl, private and public investments in eastern 
Germany in 1994 will probably rise to 160 million marks, a level 
of investments that was not even reached during the so-called 
economic miracle years. Germany is heading toward a good 
future, said Kohl. The size of unemployment is still dramatic, 
therefore all efforts will be be made to guarantee growth and 
employment opportunities. In Gera itself, a new Benefits 
Department of the Federal Insurance Fund for Office Employees 
will be set up, with 1,000 jobs. 
  Earlier on, Thuringian Minister-President Bernhard Vogel had 
pointed out the difficult situation in East Thuringia. "Nowhere 
else in the world has uranium ore extraction caused such damage 
as here," he said. Federal Economic Minister Guenter Rexrodt 
promised further support for the restructuring of the region. 
The general redevelopment of Saxony and Thuringia will last up 
to 15 years and cost about 13 million marks, he said. But the 
federal enterprise Wismut GmbH also represent a major economic 
factor, he said. The uranium ore extraction areas are 
developing into model areas for environmental and redevelopment 
technology. 

</TEXT>

