<H3> <TI>   Bonn, Lufthansa Agree on Privatization Terms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn, Lufthansa Agree on Privatization Terms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505123094 Berlin DIE WELT in German 5 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0505123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Welt-Nachrichtendienst" report: "Lufthansa To Be </F>
Privatized"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The Federal Government and Lufthansa have 
agreed on how the pension claims of the employees are to be 
protected when the corporation is privatized. This cleared the 
last obstacle for a rights issue and the withdrawal of the 
government from the airline. 
  The Federal Government currently holds 51.4 percent of 
Lufthansa. If the government does not participate in the rights 
issue, its holding will fall below 50 percent. As a result, the 
corporation falls out of the government and laender (VBL) 
pension plan, where Lufthansa employees currently have their 
pension insurance. 
  The agreement envisages that the VBL will continue to pay 
the 
pensions of Lufthansa's current 5,500 retirees. For that 
purpose, the government will pay about 1 billion marks [DM] in 
15 annual installments. For the active employees, currently 
numbering about 50,000, Lufthansa will found a company pension 
fund, into which the government will pay DM500 million over 10 
years. The trade unions have still to agree to this settlement. 
  Board of Governors Chairman Wolfgang Roeller announced a 
speedy capital increase of "more than DM1 billion." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

