<H3> <TI>   Economics Ministry Reports Orders Increase in March </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economics Ministry Reports Orders Increase in March </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505122894 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
5 May 94 p 15 </F>

<F P=103> AU0505122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["hal" report: "Orders Received Increasing Strongly"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn, 4 May -- In March, orders received in the 
processing industry in western Germany rose 3 percent -- 
seasonally adjusted for price changes -- compared with the 
previous month. In February, they also went up by 3 percent. 
In particular, foreign demand continued to rise clearly, namely 
by 6 percent. Orders by domestic customers, on the other hand, 
rose only by 1 percent, the FRG Economics Ministry in Bonn 
reports. The greatest increase was reported by the investment 
goods sector with a total of +\5 percent. The basic materials 
and producer goods industry registered 3 percent more orders. 
In contrast, business deals for the producers of durable 
consumer goods went down by 4 percent. 
  The more informative two-month comparison (February/March 
compared with December/January) showed an average increase in 
orders by 5 percent for the processing industry. In these two 
months foreign business expanded by 7.5 percent, while domestic 
demand went up by 4 percent. The basic materials and producer 
goods sector registered the highest increase with 6.5 percent. 
In the investment goods sector and the durable consumer goods 
industry orders went up 5.5 percent and 2 percent respectively. 
All together, in February and March 6.4 percent more orders 
were placed than during the same months last year. 

</TEXT>

