<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mitterrand Rejects Rejoining NATO Command </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mitterrand Rejects Rejoining NATO Command </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505172194 Paris AFP in English 1659 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0505172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, May 5 (AFP) -- President Francois Mitterrand 
said Thursday [5 May] that France could not consider rejoining 
NATO's integrated command because it wanted to keep its 
independent nuclear deterrent. 
  "For the moment, French nuclear weapons are not at 
everyone's 
disposal, they are under sole French control," the socialist 
president said in an address at the presidential palace to 
French military and civilian officials. 
  Mitterrand said control of the nuclear weapons could not be 
handed over to an international authority, adding that he stood 
by the late president Charles de Gaulle's 1966 decision to pull 
out of the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation's integrated 
command. 
  "I firmly maintain this decision. Nohing will make me change 
it," Mitterrand said. 
  Referring to the "tragic solitude of those who have the 
power 
to decide," the president said that the decision to use nuclear 
weapons must rest with the head of state because of the short 
time available to "respond to a threat of aggression." 
  Mitterrand spoke after he and his conservative government 
adopted a bill setting out French defence options for the next 
six years. 
  His audience Thursday included Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur and Defence Minister Francois Leotard. 
  The head of state and the government disagreed on two issues 
-- whether or not to resume nuclear testing at Mururoa in the 
Pacific and the fate of nuclear weapons buried in silos on the 
Albion plateau in southeastern France. 
  Mitterrand opposes resumption of nuclear testing, favoured 
by 
the right, and wants to keep the Albion site operational. 
  Much of the governing right-wing coalition wants to abandon 
strategic missiles in favour of airborne nuclear weapons. 
France also has nuclear missile-armed submarines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64761 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu088_i_94003" </HT>


