<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   D66 Leader: `Purple' Coalition Formation `Difficult' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    D66 Leader: `Purple' Coalition Formation `Difficult' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0605133294 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 6 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BR0605133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Democrats Predicts Difficulty in </F>
Forming `Purple' Government"] 
  [Text] D66 [Democrats 66] leader Van Mierlo predicted that 
the creation of a "purple" government comprising the D66, the 
PvdA [Labor Party], and the VVD [People's Party for Freedom and 
Democracy] will be "an extremely delicate and difficult 
operation, full of difficulties." Van Mierlo said this Thursday 
[5 May] following the first meeting in Amsterdam of the new 
24-member group. 
  The D66 had already made it clear during the election 
campaign that it would try to put together a "purple" coalition. 
However, now that the party has become the fourth largest, 
behind the VVD, it is more difficult for the D66 to serve as a 
bridge between the PvdA and the VVD. "It is easier to build a 
bridge between the PvdA and the VVD if you are in between," Van 
Mierlo said. 
  The D66 leader, who yesterday was provisionally elected 
floor 
leader, did not want to reveal anything about the way in which 
the D66 aims to achieve its goal. "The D66's scenario is to 
serve the achievement of the goal: A `purple' coalition. I am 
not holding anything back as far as that is concerned. However, 
if you want to know about strategy, how we are going to get 
where we want to go, then I would say this: That is rather 
delicate, and will have to remain secret for now." 

</TEXT>

