<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Cultivate `Political Climate' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Cultivate `Political Climate' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905151094 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 9 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0905151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Heinz Schmitz: "Only For Cultivating the </F>
Climate"] 
  [Text] The new Japanese prime minister, Tsutomu Hata, 
visited several European capitals last week. According to an 
official statement, he held talks in Bonn "in a friendly 
atmosphere" and discussed with Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl 
relations between the two countries and international affairs. 
As a routine of such talks, the Western side urges better 
access to the Japanese market, and Japan promptly promises to 
make huge efforts to reform the economic structures and open the 
markets. This also happened in Bonn. 
  Under the headline "Preparation of the World Economic 
Summit," which will take place in Naples in July, Kohl urged his 
Japanese visitor to increase support for Russia. While Germany 
has, in the past, borne the main burden, Japan has only shown a 
cold shoulder in this respect. This will hardly change in 
Naples. Nor will the chancellor's wish for increased commitment 
of Japanese companies in eastern Germany be considered as long 
as they cannot expect to get a good return on their investment. 
Both governments see themselves in one boat on their way to a 
permanent seat on the UN Security Council. Even though the 
arguments exchanged are not new, it is sensible for the chiefs 
of governments from friendly nations to meet personally at 
regular intervals. Cultivating the political climate is of 
importance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

