<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Sees No Success in Confidence-Building Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Sees No Success in Confidence-Building Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0705200094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0705200094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The United Nations does not see prospects for 
success in the efforts for implementation of the 
confidence-building measures [CBMs], and for this reason it is 
not willing to grant an extension to this process. Reliable UN 
sources told CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation] that from 
the contacts held after [UN Secretary General's special 
representative on Cyprus] Joe Clark's departure from Cyprus 
there was no evidence or developments that justify an extension 
to the process. The same sources also noted that in view of 
this situation, there is no plan to call a meeting in New York 
between President Glavkos Kliridhis and Turkish Cypriot leader 
Rauf Denktas. 
  Attention is now focused on the preparation and presentation 
of the UN secretary general's report to the Security Council in 
which the events will be reported objectively. Furthermore, the 
same UN source rejected Denktas' accusations and the British 
side's views that there were changes in the original package of 
the confidence-building measures. The UN sources clarified that 
the package of measures refers to the outline, whereas the 21 
March document refers to the ways to implement the measures. 
They also noted that the 21 March document includes serious 
improvements which are almost all to the Turkish Cypriots' 
benefit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64829 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu089_p_94001" </HT>


