<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Satisfied With U.S. Interest in FYROM </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Satisfied With U.S. Interest in FYROM </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0705174094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0705174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou and U.S. 
President Bill Clinton had a telephone conversation yesterday 
during which they agreed on the need for a speedy solution of 
the Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] 
issue. During the telephone conversation, the U.S. President 
also expressed his support for the confidence-building measures 
for the Cyprus issue which, he said, are the best hope to 
achieve progress. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos described the U.S. 
interest in a solution to the Greek-Skopje dispute as obvious. 
Venizelos added that the Ubited States understands the Greek 
positions and wants a swift solution of the issue, something 
which we want as well. 
  Next week there will be a meeting in New York between 
Ambassador Khristos Zakharakis, Foreign Ministry director 
general and UN Mediator Cyrus Vance. 

</TEXT>

