<F P=100> WEST EUROPE ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Addresses East-West Economic Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rexrodt Addresses East-West Economic Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0705170094 Hamburg DPA in German 0917 GMT 7 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0705170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw (DPA) -- Federal Economics Minister Guenter 
Rexrodt called upon the East and Central European countries on 7 
May to create clear investment conditions. "We need clear and 
reliable investment conditions for the whole investment period. 
Those who cannot guarantee this should not be surprised if no 
investment is made," he said in Warsaw at the East-West economic 
meeting of highly industrialized nations (G-7) with 10 Central 
and East European reform states (E-10). 
  Deviating from his prepared text, Rexrodt listed details: 
"In the energy sector, we will need such stability for a period 
of between 20 and 30 years. A calculable tax system is 
indispensable. Taxes must promote investment and should not 
burden investment unreasonably." Other points, according to 
Rexrodt, are a functioning banking system allowing the 
retransfer of capital invested, the acquisition of real estate, 
and the reduction of bureaucracy. In addition, exports must be 
possible, and intellectual property must be protected. 
  Rexrodt thereby referred to concrete complaints of business 
people doing business in the East. He said that last year, 
approximately 10 percent of German investment abroad went to 
Central and East Europe. By the end of 1993, the Federal 
Government assumed guarantees for investment totalling 2.9 
billion German marks. Four-fifths of this sum went to the 
Visegrad countries (Hungary, the Czech Republic, Poland, and 
Slovakia). The minister emphatically advocated greater access 
for the East European countries to Western markets. 
  To clarify practical problems, a business forum of economic 
experts having practical experience preceded the meeting. The 
participants published a "Warsaw Business Statement" on 6 May, 
in which they set the goal for themselves to carry out direct 
investment in the E-10 countries of approximately $200 billion 
by the year 2000. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

