<H3> <TI>   EU Grants Loan for Palestinian Police Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Grants Loan for Palestinian Police Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0605131794 London REUTER Textline Database in English 5 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0605131794 </F>
<F P=104>  London REUTER Textline Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article from Brussels EUROPE: "Commission </F>
Grants ECU10 Million in Aid To Help Create a Palestinian Police 
Force"] 
  [Text] The European Commission took the provisions required 
to make concrete the decision of principle (adopted by the 
General Affairs Council of 18/19 April in the framework of joint 
action under the CFSP [Common Foreign and Security Policy] "in 
supporting the peace process in the Middle East") of granting 
ECU10 million to assist in creating a Palestinian police force 
in the Occupied Territories. Mr. Marin informed Mr. 'Arafat 
this very Wednesday [4 May], in Cairo, of the Community 
decision. It is now up to the Palestinian authorities to submit 
operational projects that the Commission can finance (equipment, 
wages, means of transport, etc., but excluding the purchase of 
weapons). This measure is only one aspect of Community aid to 
the Occupied Territories. The ECU10 million are from the 1994 
budget, from a 50 million package for aid to these territories, 
33 million of which have already been committed for housing, 
schools, and technical assistance. For the 1994/98 period as a 
whole, the Union is committed to supplying ECU500 million for 
economic development in the Occupied Territories. The joint 
action under CFSP decided on 19 April contains several other 
initiatives alongside the emergency assistance for the police 
force. 

</TEXT>

